lk: A Discourse on Political Consciuosness|last=Anand|first=J S|publisher=Vishwabharati Research Centre|year=2017|isbn=978-9386242327|location=India|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Anand|first=J S|title=IN LOVE WITH COSMOS: A WORK OF SPIRITUALITY AND COSMIC CULTURE|publisher=Earth Vision Publications|year=2017|isbn=9789384922436|location=Gurugram Haryana India|pages=|translator-last=Mohammadi|translator-first=Nargues}}\n*{{Cite book|title=MASTERS OF CREATIVE IMPULSE: MOST VIBRANT VOICES FROM CONTEMPORARY INDIAN ENGLISH POETRY|publisher=VISHWABHARATI AND THEMATICS INDOTECH|year=2017|isbn=9789386242518|editor-last=ANAND|editor-first=MANMINDER SINGH ANAND|location=NEW DELHI INDIA|pages=|editor-last2=Rathore|editor-first2=M A}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Anand|first=J S|title=GEET UNSUNG SONG OF ETERNITY: A SEQUEL TO JOHN MILTON'S 'PARADISE LOST' (2ND ED.)|publisher=Aditya Prakashan In Association With Vishwabharati Research Centre|year=2018|isbn=9789387651883|location=New Delhi India|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Anand|first=J S|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/The_Ganturbury_Tales.html?id=In8-ygEACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=THE GANTURBURY TALES: A SEQUEL TO GEOFFREY CHAUCER'S 'THE CANTERBURY TALES'|publisher=Authorpress|year=2018|isbn=9789388008938|location=New Delhi India|pages=}}\n*{{Cite journal|last=Anand|first=J S|date=2018-02-24|title=POETIC CREATION AND RECREATION: THE MAGIC SPELL AND THE CLOUD SYNDROME|url=|journal=International Seminar on Novel Issues in Indian Writing in English|publisher=Authorpress|publication-place=New Delhi India|volume=|pages=53-57|isbn=9789387651166|via=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Anand|first=J S|url=https://www.amazon.in/Satanic-Empire-Jernail-Singh-Anand/dp/9383755997|title=The Satanic Empire|publisher=Global Fraternity of Poets|year=2019|isbn=9789383755998|location=Gurgaon Haryana India|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Anand|first=J S|title=VOICES FROM THE VOID|publisher=Global Fraternity of Poets|year=2019|isbn=9789383755875|location=Gurgaon Haryana India|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=PAN INDIAN POETRY IN ENGLISH SPANNING FIRST TWO DECADES OF 21ST CENTURY|publisher=Today and Tomorrow's Printers and Publishers|year=2019|isbn=9788170196495|editor-last=Anand|editor-first=J S|location=New Delhi India|pages=|editor-last2=Chakraborti|editor-first2=Basudeb}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Anand|first=J S|url=https://www.amazon.in/FIGHTING-FLAMES-Dr-J-Anand/dp/9383755830|title=FIGHTING THE FLAMES|publisher=Global Fraternity of Poets|year=2019|isbn=9789383755837|location=Gurugram Haryana India|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Anand|first=J S|url=https://www.amazon.in/BROKEN-NARRATIVE-JERNAIL-SINGH-ANAND/dp/B0849T7ZCW/ref=sr_1_6?qid=1585744205&refinements=p_27%3ADr+Jernail+Singh+Anand&s=books&sr=1-6|title=The Broken Narrative|publisher=YAYATI MADAN G GANDHI GROUP OF PUBLICATION|year=2020|isbn=9788194485827|location=Hisar Haryana India|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=LILACS IN BLOOM|publisher=The Poetry Society of India|others=A Project of Galaxy International Foundation|year=2020|isbn=9789389213133|editor-last=Anand|editor-first=J S|location=Hisar Haryana India|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|title=POETS & POETRY: SPACES WITHIN & WITHOUT|publisher=Earth Vision Publications|year=2020|isbn=9788194485841|editor-last=Anand|editor-first=J S|location=Gurugram Haryana India|pages=|editor-last2=Jaggi|editor-first2=Parneet}}\n*{{Cite book|title=DYNAMICS OF POETRY: THE SAID AND THE UNSAID|publisher=Earth Vision Publication|year=2020|isbn=9788194485872|editor-last=Anand|editor-first=J S|location=Gurugram Haryana India|pages=|editor-last2=Jaggi|editor-first2=Parneet}}\n\n==Major awards and recognition==\n*Member of the Commission for the International Best Poet Award 2017 of the World Nations Writers Union, Kazakhstan<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wnwu.org/index.php/en/|title=High Level Officials of THE WORLD NATION WRITERS UNION OF KAZAKHSTAN (WNWU)|last=Garrido|first=Carlos Hugo|date=2017-10-09|website=World Nation Writers' Union|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-07-12}}</ref>\n*First Ambassador of the World Union of Poets, Italy. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atunispoetry.com/2016/04/25/world-union-of-poets-celebrates-the-power-of-poetry-aims-to-bring-a-revolution-in-the-consciousness-of-time-issued-by-dr-j-s-anand-ambassador-and-general-director-wup/|title=WORLD UNION OF POETS CELEBRATES THE POWER OF POETRY: AIMS TO BRING A REVOLUTION IN THE CONSCIOUSNESS OF TIME, ISSUED BY Dr. J.S. ANAND, AMBASSADOR AND GENERAL DIRECTOR WUP|last=BORTOLAZZI|first=SILVANO|date=2016-04-25|website=ATUNIS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref>\n*Chairperson of World Foundation for Peace, and Writers International Foundation<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tribuneindia.com/news/bathinda/poems-rediscover-island-called-self/216121.html|title=Poems rediscover \u2018island called self\u2019|date=1 April 2016|website=The Tribune}}</ref>\n*Dr Anand  evolved the theory of BIOTEXT in Literary Theory<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://atunispoetry.com/2017/10/11/j-s-anands-theory-of-biotext-and-critical-perspectives-on-his-poetic-and-spiritual-creed-first-edition-2016-by-dr-roghayeh-farsi-author-introduction/|title=J.S. Anand\u2019s Theory of Biotext And Critical Perspectives on His Poetic and Spiritual Creed (First Edition, 2016) /  By Dr Roghayeh Farsi (Author, Introduction)|date=2017-10-11|work=Galaktika Poetike  \"ATUNIS\"|access-date=2018-04-30|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*Cross for Peace for his Lifetime Achievement in the Field of Poetry and Peace by Wolrd Union of Poets. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nation.com.pk/11-May-2016/pak-poet-to-get-cross-for-peace-award|title=Pak poet to get Cross for Peace Award|last=Ahmad|first=Israr|date=2016-05-11|website=The Nation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref>\n*2017: Art4peace award by Art4peace Foundation, Hollywood, USA\n*2017: World epitome of leadership award World Institute of Peace, Nigeria\n*2017: Honored with Lord of World Peace and Literature Award, conferred at India World Poetry Festival, held at Ramoji City, Hyderabad 13-14th Oct, 2017\n*Dr M S Randhawa Award for Promotion of Art & Culture of Punjab Conferred\n*2009: Recipient of Penguin Rising Personalities of India Award \n*2008: Best Educationist Award for the outstanding achievements in academics by National and International Compendium in New Delhi\n*Avantika educational excellence award by Sri Rajiv Gandhi Foundation Ratia\n*Founder President, Philosophique Poetica [De-Anand] - A Portal for Poetry, Art, Peace and Philosophy\n\n==Membership and appointments==\n*Member, Syndicate, Punjabi University, Patiala.\n*Fellow, Punjabi University, Patiala\n*Member, Board of Studies, Guru Kashi University, Talwandi Sabo\n*National Vice-president, International Human Rights Observatory [ihro]\n*Patron and Honorary Chief Editor: Symphony International \n*Life Member: [[United Writers' Association|United Writers Association]], Chennai\t\n*Chairman of the International Society of Poets\t\n*Chairman of the Sufi Arts Foundation\t\n*Member of the Association of Indian College Principals\t\n*Patron: Academic Earth Institute of Multi-studies\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anand, Jernail Singh}}\n[[Category:Poets from Punjab, India]]\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Drsbgarg", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added References", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jernail_Singh_Anand"}
{"title_page": "Leo Abse", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image = Leo-Abse.jpg\n|honorific-suffix = \n|office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]]\n|predecessor = New constituency\n|successor = [[Paul Murphy, Baron Murphy of Torfaen|Paul Murphy]]\n|term_start = 9 June 1983\n|term_end = 18 May 1987\n|constituency_MP2 = [[Pontypool (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontypool]]\n|predecessor2 = [[Granville West, Baron Granville-West|Granville West]]\n|successor2 = Constituency abolished\n|term_start2 = [[1958 Pontypool by-election|10 November 1958]]\n|term_end2 = 13 May 1983\n|birth_name = Leopold Abse\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1917|4|22|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Cardiff]], Wales\n|death_date = {{death date and age|2008|8|19|1917|4|22|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[London]], England\n|nationality = British\n|party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|alma_mater = [[London School of Economics]]\n|occupation = {{hlist|Author|MP|[[solicitor]]}}\n}}\n'''Leopold Abse''' (22 April 1917 \u2013 19 August 2008)<ref name=\"Times obit\">{{cite news |newspaper=The Times |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article4573641.ece?token=null&offset=12&page=2 |title=Leo Abse: MP who fought to reform homosexuality and divorce laws |date=21 August 2008 |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531134154/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article4573641.ece?token=null&offset=12&page=2 |archivedate=31 May 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> was a Welsh lawyer and politician. He was a [[Welsh Labour]] MP for nearly 30 years, noted for promoting [[private member's bill]]s to decriminalise male [[homosexuality|homosexual relations]] and liberalise the [[divorce]] laws. During his parliamentary career, Abse introduced more private member's bills than any other parliamentarian in the 20th century.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> After his retirement from Parliament he wrote several books about politics, based on his interest in [[psychoanalysis]].\n\n==Family and background==\nLeo Abse was one of the sons of Rudolf Abse, a [[Jews|Jewish]] solicitor and cinema owner who lived in [[Cardiff]]. His maternal grandfather, Tobias, had emigrated to Wales from [[Siemiatycze]], a Polish town then located within the Russian Empire.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> His grandmother came from Germany. Abse's younger brother [[Dannie Abse]] (1923\u20132014) was a poet, and his older brother [[Wilfred Abse]] (1915\u20132005) a psychoanalyst. He also had a sister, Hulda.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> Abse attended [[Howard Gardens High School]] in Cardiff and then the [[London School of Economics]], where he studied law. Having joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in 1934, he clandestinely visited [[Spain]] during the closing months of the [[Spanish Civil War]], in 1939.<ref name=\"Times obit\" />\n\nAbse married Marjorie Davies in 1955. They had two children: [[Tobias Abse|Tobias]] (now a [[Marxism|Marxist]] historian) and Bathsheba. Marjorie died in 1996. His second marriage was to Ania Czepulkowska, in 2000, when Abse was 83 and Czepulkowska 33. Abse died on 19 August 2008. According to a newspaper report, he left his \u00a31.2m estate to his second wife, with no financial provision for his children or grandchildren.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1289930/Family-s-fury-Labour-MP-leaves-1m-Polish-wife.html?ito=feeds-newsxml |location=London |publisher=[[Daily Mail]] |work=[[Mail Online]] |first1=George |last1=Arbuthnott |first2=Jonathan |last2=Petre |title=Family's fury as Labour MP leaves \u00a31m to Polish wife |date=26 June 2010 |archivedate=25 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140425033502/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1289930/Family-s-fury-Labour-MP-leaves-1m-Polish-wife.html?ito=feeds-news.xml |url-status=dead }}</ref> Some 10 years after her husband died, Mrs Czepulkowska-Abse broke her silence and spoke to the ''[[South Wales Argus]]'' and paid tribute to her husband. She confirmed that she is still living and working in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/16612363.widow-ania-czepulkowska-abse-of-former-torfaen-mp-leo-abse-has-broken-her-silence-and-pays-tribute-to-him-in-her-first-interview-since-his-death-10-years-ago/|title=Leo Abse's widow breaks silence and pays tribute to husband in first interview since his death 10 years ago|work=South Wales Argus}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/16617320.remembering-the-gay-rights-champion-leo-abse-who-died-10-years-ago/|title=Remembering the gay rights champion Leo Abse who died 10-years ago|work=South Wales Argus}}</ref>\n\n==Political involvement==\nDuring the Second World War Abse served in the [[Royal Air Force]]. He was in [[Cairo]] in 1944 when some of the British military personnel stationed there set up a \"[[Forces Parliament]]\" in which they debated the structure of society they wanted to see in the post-war world. Abse's idealistic left-wing views were fully in tune with the majority opinion among the lower ranks at its meetings, but the existence of the \"Parliament\" disturbed the senior officers. When Abse moved a motion supporting [[nationalization]] of the [[Bank of England]] he was arrested and the Forces Parliament was forcibly dissolved.\n\nAfter the end of the war Abse set up in practice as a solicitor in Cardiff. In 1951 he established his own law firm, Leo Abse & Cohen, which eventually grew to be the biggest in the city. He was also elected as Chairman of Cardiff Labour Party for two years from 1951, relinquishing the post when he was elected to Cardiff City Council.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leo Abse |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 August 2008 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/2590828/Leo-Abse.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820222718/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/2590828/Leo-Abse.html |archivedate=20 August 2008 }}</ref> Abse fought the safe Conservative seat of [[Cardiff North (UK Parliament constituency)|Cardiff North]] in the [[1955 United Kingdom general election|1955 general election]], and was defeated.\n\n==In Parliament==\n[[Granville West, Baron Granville-West|Granville West]], the Labour MP for [[Pontypool (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontypool]] and, like Abse, a solicitor, was awarded one of the first [[life peerage]]s in 1958. Unusually for a town in the South Wales valleys at that time, the [[National Union of Mineworkers (Great Britain)|National Union of Mineworkers]] was not in control of the nomination of West's successor as Labour candidate, since Pontypool was a centre of the railway industry. Abse won the candidature and then won the seat at the [[1958 Pontypool by-election|by-election]].\n\nIn the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] Abse swiftly acquired a reputation for independence of spirit. He made a point of dressing flamboyantly on Budget day, and liked to drop references from [[Sigmund Freud|Freudian]] [[psychotherapy]] into his speeches. Although his abilities might have taken him to high office, Abse remained a backbench MP. This factor, together with the fact that he had a safe seat, freed him from the restrictions that prevented most other MPs from taking up controversial subjects.\n\nIn 1963, Abse was selected in third place in the ballot for [[Private Member's Bill]]s and introduced the [[Matrimonial Causes Bill]], which simplified and made easier the legal process of [[divorce]].\n\nIn 1957 the [[Wolfenden Report]] had recommended that the law be changed to decriminalise consenting male [[homosexuality|homosexual]] sex, but the government had taken no action. Abse began to promote [[Sexual Offences Act 1967|a Bill]] to put Wolfenden's recommendations into law in February 1962. He kept pressing the issue and, after [[Humphry Berkeley]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP for [[Lancaster (UK Parliament constituency)|Lancaster]]) lost his seat in the [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966 general election]], Abse became the main sponsor for the legalisation. Although with the Labour landslide of 1966 there was a majority for the bill, it was still vulnerable but Abse persuaded [[Roy Jenkins]] to give the measure government time, which eventually saw the bill through onto the statute book.<ref>{{cite news |author=Patricia Brent and Leo Abse |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/gay_rights/12005.shtml |title=Why should homosexuality be decriminalised? |date=20 December 1966 |publisher=[[BBC Archives]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818134241/http://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/gay_rights/12005.shtml |archivedate=18 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 1968 he was appointed to a [[Home Office]] advisory committee on the penal system. He was elected Chairman of the group of Welsh Labour MPs in 1971.\n\nIn 1973, Abse requested that the government ban the rock singer [[Alice Cooper]] and his group from performing in England, stating that Cooper was \"peddling the culture of the [[concentration camp]]\". Abse said: \"Pop is one thing, anthems of [[necrophilia]] are quite another\".<ref>Source: booklet of \"The life and crimes of [[Alice Cooper]]\" 4 CD box set.</ref>\n\nAbse was chosen as chairman of a [[select committee]] on [[abortion]] from 1975 to 1977. His report advocated restrictions on abortion, including a lowering of the time limit within which abortion was legal from 28 weeks. He fought in the House of Commons for the enactment of his committee's recommendations, and continued the fight in 1980 when the Conservative MP [[John Corrie]] proposed a bill along similar lines: Abse refused to compromise on a limit of 24 weeks.\n\nAbse was an opponent of [[devolution]] when it was proposed in the late 1970s. He also proposed a separate referendum on whether the [[Shetland Islands]] ought to be part of a devolved [[Scotland]]. Abse was briefly chairman of the Welsh Affairs Select Committee when it was first set up, but resigned in November 1981. One of the reasons he opposed devolution was that he thought some in Wales, whom he called \"fanatics\", wanted to use it to promote the use of the [[Welsh language]].\n\nAbse added to his reputation for taking maverick stances by strongly urging that British forces be withdrawn from [[Northern Ireland]]. He opposed [[nuclear power]] and [[nuclear weapons]], and criticised [[Margaret Thatcher]] for insisting that [[Argentina]] unconditionally surrender over the [[Falkland Islands]]. He supported British membership of the [[European Union|European Communities]]. His support for liberal divorce laws led him to propose a new 'child-centred' divorce reform in the early 1980s; the bill was piloted by [[Martin Stevens]], Conservative MP for [[Fulham (UK Parliament constituency)|Fulham]].\n\nAbse was elected for the renamed seat of [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]] in 1983, but retired from Parliament in 1987. His nomination for a seat in the House of Lords was vetoed by Margaret Thatcher.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\">{{cite web|last1=Goodman|first1=Geoffrey|title=Leo Abse |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/aug/21/labour.houseofcommons |website=The Guardian |accessdate=16 June 2017 |date=20 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement and later writings==\nThe first of the books Abse wrote following retirement, ''Margaret, Daughter of Beatrice'' (1989), is a \"psycho-biography\" of Margaret Thatcher, taking its title from the observation that while Mrs Thatcher frequently referred to her father, she claimed not to have had anything to say to her mother from the age of 15.\n\nIn ''Wotan, My Enemy'' (1994) Abse took a psychoanalytic approach to explaining the origin of British hostility to Germany and the idea of the European Union. In ''The Man behind the Smile: Tony Blair and the Politics of Perversion'' (1996), Abse highlighted some of the aspects of [[Tony Blair]] that were later to be cited by Blair's opponents on the left. A revised edition, ''Tony Blair: The Man who Lost His Smile'' (2003), was published in the United States). In this edition Abse took the opportunity to claim that he had paid off a [[blackmail]]er who had been targeting a fellow Welsh MP [[George Thomas, 1st Viscount Tonypandy|George Thomas]] (Speaker of the House of Commons from 1976 to 1983), on the basis of Thomas's (closeted) homosexuality.\n\nFinally, in ''Fellatio, Masochism, Politics and Love'' (1997), Abse drew attention to the fact that fellatio had been unspoken of a generation before but had since come to be seen as an essential part of casual sexual relationships. He analysed the tendency for men to engage in risky behaviour by placing their trust in women whom they barely knew and linked it to political developments.\n\n==Memorial==\nA bust of Abse was unveiled at the [[National Museum of Wales]] in Cardiff on 22 October 2009. The sculpture was funded by the firm of solicitors he founded, Leo Abse and Cohen, and was made by Abse's second cousin, Luke Shepherd.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/8320344.stm |title=Bust of radical MP Abse unveiled |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=22 October 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025235012/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/8320344.stm |archivedate=25 October 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nAbse was played by actor Anthony O'Donnell in the TV series ''A Very English Scandal''.\n\n==Publications==\n*''Private Member'' (MacDonald, London, 1973)\n*''Margaret, Daughter of Beatrice'' (Jonathan Cape, London, 1989)\n*''Wotan, My Enemy'' (Robson Books, London, 1994)\n*''Tony Blair: The Man behind the Smile'' (Robson Books, London, 1996)\n*''Fellatio, Masochism, Politics and Love'' (Robson Books, London, 1997)\n*''Tony Blair: The Man who Lost his Smile'' (Robson Books, London, 2003)\n*''The Bi-sexuality of Daniel Defoe: a psychoanalytic survey of the man and his works'' (Karnac Books, London, 2006)\n\n==Further reading==\n*\"Leo Abse\" in ''Parliamentary Profiles A\u2013D'' by [[Andrew Roth]] (Parliamentary Profiles Services Ltd, London, 1984)\n*''Peers, Queers and Commons'' by Stephen Jeffery-Poulter (Routledge, London, 1991)\n*''Quest for Justice: Towards Homosexual Emancipation'' by Antony Grey ([[Sinclair-Stevenson]], London, 1992)\n*\"The Troublemakers...\" by Stephen Cretney, in ''The Continuing Evolution of Family Law'', edited by N. Lowe and G. Douglas (Jordans, Bristol, 2009).\n*''Family Law in the Twentieth Century: A History'' (Oxford, UK: OUP, 2003)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite web|last1=Goodman|first1=Geoffrey|title=Leo Abse|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/aug/21/labour.houseofcommons|website=The Guardian|accessdate=16 June 2017|date=20 August 2008}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/transformingsociety/private-lives/relationships/collections1/sexual-offences-act-1967/leo-abse-mp/ Leo Abse- 50th Anniversary of the 1967 Sexual Offences Act - UK Parliament Living Heritage]\n*[https://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article632537.ece Leo Abse and his brother Dannie] - a joint interview in ''The Times'' November 2006\n*[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/leo-abse-labour-mp-whose-parliamentary-bills-helped-liberalise-british-society-904024.html Obituary in The Independent] by [[Tam Dalyell]]\n*[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article4573641.ece Times obit, August 2008]\n*[http://paulflynnmp.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/08/leo-abse---backbenchers-backbencher.html Paul Flynn MP: Leo Abse - backbenchers\u2019 backbencher - Chutzpah and contentment August 2008]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/gayrights/story/0,,2109785,00.html Coming out of the dark ages] (article from [[The Observer]], 24 June 2007, which includes an interview with Abse)\n*[http://respectance.com/Leo_Abse/memorial Leo Abse Memorial]\n*[http://www.socialistunity.com/?p=2746 Socialist Unity: Remember the good soldier, August 2008]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Granville West, Baron Granville-West|Granville West]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title =[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Pontypool (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontypool]]|years=[[1958 Pontypool by-election|1958]]\u2013[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\n}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]]|years=[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]\n}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Murphy (British politician)|Paul Murphy]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abse, Leo}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Cardiff]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cardiff]]\n[[Category:People from Cwmbran]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1955\u20131959]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1959\u20131964]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1964\u20131966]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1966\u20131970]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:Welsh Jews]]\n[[Category:Welsh people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:British people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Abse family|Leo]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour councillors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=July 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|image = Leo-Abse.jpg\n|honorific-suffix = \n|office = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]]<br>for [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]]\n|predecessor = New constituency\n|successor = [[Paul Murphy, Baron Murphy of Torfaen|Paul Murphy]]\n|term_start = 9 June 1983\n|term_end = 18 May 1987\n|constituency_MP2 = [[Pontypool (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontypool]]\n|predecessor2 = [[Granville West, Baron Granville-West|Granville West]]\n|successor2 = Constituency abolished\n|term_start2 = [[1958 Pontypool by-election|10 November 1958]]\n|term_end2 = 13 May 1983\n|birth_name = Leopold Abse\n|birth_date = {{Birth date|1917|4|22|df=y}}\n|birth_place = [[Cardiff]], Wales\n|death_date = {{death date and age|2008|8|19|1917|4|22|df=y}}\n|death_place = [[London]], England\n|nationality = British\n|party = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|alma_mater = [[London School of Economics]]\n|occupation = {{hlist|Author|MP|[[solicitor]]}}\n}}\n'''Leopold Abse''' (22 April 1917 \u2013 19 August 2008)<ref name=\"Times obit\">{{cite news |newspaper=The Times |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article4573641.ece?token=null&offset=12&page=2 |title=Leo Abse: MP who fought to reform homosexuality and divorce laws |date=21 August 2008 |location=London |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531134154/http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article4573641.ece?token=null&offset=12&page=2 |archivedate=31 May 2010 |url-status=dead}}</ref> was a Welsh lawyer and politician. He was a [[Welsh Labour]] MP for nearly 30 years, noted for promoting [[private member's bill]]s to decriminalise male [[homosexuality|homosexual relations]] and liberalise the [[divorce]] laws. During his parliamentary career, Abse introduced more private member's bills than any other parliamentarian in the 20th century.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> After his retirement from Parliament he wrote several books about politics, based on his interest in [[psychoanalysis]].\n\n==Family and background==\nLeo Abse was one of the sons of Rudolf Abse, a [[Jews|Jewish]] solicitor and cinema owner who lived in [[Cardiff]]. His maternal grandfather, Tobias, had emigrated to Wales from [[Siemiatycze]], a Polish town then located within the Russian Empire.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> His grandmother came from Germany. Abse's younger brother [[Dannie Abse]] (1923\u20132014) was a poet, and his older brother [[Wilfred Abse]] (1915\u20132005) a psychoanalyst. He also had a sister, Hulda.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\" /> Abse attended [[Howard Gardens High School]] in Cardiff and then the [[London School of Economics]], where he studied law. Having joined the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] in 1934, he clandestinely visited [[Spain]] during the closing months of the [[Spanish Civil War]], in 1939.<ref name=\"Times obit\" />\n\nAbse married Marjorie Davies in 1955. They had two children: [[Tobias Abse|Tobias]] (now a [[Marxism|Marxist]] historian) and Bathsheba. Marjorie died in 1996. His second marriage was to Ania Czepulkowska, in 2000, when Abse was 83 and Czepulkowska 33. Abse died on 19 August 2008. According to a newspaper report, he left his \u00a31.2m estate to his second wife, with no financial provision for his children or grandchildren.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1289930/Family-s-fury-Labour-MP-leaves-1m-Polish-wife.html?ito=feeds-newsxml |location=London |publisher=[[Daily Mail]] |work=[[Mail Online]] |first1=George |last1=Arbuthnott |first2=Jonathan |last2=Petre |title=Family's fury as Labour MP leaves \u00a31m to Polish wife |date=26 June 2010 |archivedate=25 April 2014 |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20140425033502/http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1289930/Family-s-fury-Labour-MP-leaves-1m-Polish-wife.html?ito=feeds-news.xml |url-status=dead }}</ref> Some 10 years after her husband died, Mrs Czepulkowska-Abse broke her silence and spoke to the ''[[South Wales Argus]]'' and paid tribute to her husband. She confirmed that she is still living and working in London.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/16612363.widow-ania-czepulkowska-abse-of-former-torfaen-mp-leo-abse-has-broken-her-silence-and-pays-tribute-to-him-in-her-first-interview-since-his-death-10-years-ago/|title=Leo Abse's widow breaks silence and pays tribute to husband in first interview since his death 10 years ago|work=South Wales Argus}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.southwalesargus.co.uk/news/16617320.remembering-the-gay-rights-champion-leo-abse-who-died-10-years-ago/|title=Remembering the gay rights champion Leo Abse who died 10-years ago|work=South Wales Argus}}</ref>\n\n==Political involvement==\nDuring the Second World War Abse served in the [[Royal Air Force]]. He was in [[Cairo]] in 1944 when some of the British military personnel stationed there set up a \"[[Forces Parliament]]\" in which they debated the structure of society they wanted to see in the post-war world. Abse's idealistic left-wing views were fully in tune with the majority opinion among the lower ranks at its meetings, but the existence of the \"Parliament\" disturbed the senior officers. When Abse moved a motion supporting [[nationalization]] of the [[Bank of England]] he was arrested and the Forces Parliament was forcibly dissolved.\n\nAfter the end of the war Abse set up in practice as a solicitor in Cardiff. In 1951 he established his own law firm, Leo Abse & Cohen, which eventually grew to be the biggest in the city. He was also elected as Chairman of Cardiff Labour Party for two years from 1951, relinquishing the post when he was elected to Cardiff City Council.<ref>{{cite news |title=Leo Abse |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=20 August 2008 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/2590828/Leo-Abse.html |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080820222718/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/2590828/Leo-Abse.html |archivedate=20 August 2008 }}</ref> Abse fought the safe Conservative seat of [[Cardiff North (UK Parliament constituency)|Cardiff North]] in the [[1955 United Kingdom general election|1955 general election]], and was defeated.\n\n==In Parliament==\n[[Granville West, Baron Granville-West|Granville West]], the Labour MP for [[Pontypool (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontypool]] and, like Abse, a solicitor, was awarded one of the first [[life peerage]]s in 1958. Unusually for a town in the South Wales valleys at that time, the [[National Union of Mineworkers (Great Britain)|National Union of Mineworkers]] was not in control of the nomination of West's successor as Labour candidate, since Pontypool was a centre of the railway industry. Abse won the candidature and then won the seat at the [[1958 Pontypool by-election|by-election]].\n\nIn the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] Abse swiftly acquired a reputation for independence of spirit. He made a point of dressing flamboyantly on Budget day, and liked to drop references from [[Sigmund Freud|Freudian]] [[psychotherapy]] into his speeches. Although his abilities might have taken him to high office, Abse remained a backbench MP. This factor, together with the fact that he had a safe seat, freed him from the restrictions that prevented most other MPs from taking up controversial subjects.\n\nIn 1963, Abse was selected in third place in the ballot for [[Private Member's Bill]]s and introduced the [[Matrimonial Causes Bill]], which simplified and made easier the legal process of [[divorce]].\n\nIn 1957 the [[Wolfenden Report]] had recommended that the law be changed to decriminalise consenting male [[homosexuality|homosexual]] sex, but the government had taken no action. Abse began to promote [[Sexual Offences Act 1967|a Bill]] to put Wolfenden's recommendations into law in February 1962. He kept pressing the issue and, after [[Humphry Berkeley]] ([[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] MP for [[Lancaster (UK Parliament constituency)|Lancaster]]) lost his seat in the [[1966 United Kingdom general election|1966 general election]], Abse became the main sponsor for the legalisation. Although with the Labour landslide of 1966 there was a majority for the bill, it was still vulnerable but Abse persuaded [[Roy Jenkins]] to give the measure government time, which eventually saw the bill through onto the statute book.<ref>{{cite news |author=Patricia Brent and Leo Abse |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/gay_rights/12005.shtml |title=Why should homosexuality be decriminalised? |date=20 December 1966 |publisher=[[BBC Archives]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110818134241/http://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/gay_rights/12005.shtml |archivedate=18 August 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn 1968 he was appointed to a [[Home Office]] advisory committee on the penal system. He was elected Chairman of the group of Welsh Labour MPs in 1971.\n\nIn 1973, Abse requested that the government ban the rock singer [[Alice Cooper]] and his group from performing in England, stating that Cooper was \"peddling the culture of the [[concentration camp]]\". Abse said: \"Pop is one thing, anthems of [[necrophilia]] are quite another\".<ref>Source: booklet of \"The life and crimes of [[Alice Cooper]]\" 4 CD box set.</ref>\n\nAbse was chosen as chairman of a [[select committee]] on [[abortion]] from 1975 to 1977. His report advocated restrictions on abortion, including a lowering of the time limit within which abortion was legal from 28 weeks. He fought in the House of Commons for the enactment of his committee's recommendations, and continued the fight in 1980 when the Conservative MP [[John Corrie]] proposed a bill along similar lines: Abse refused to compromise on a limit of 24 weeks.\n\nAbse was an opponent of [[devolution]] when it was proposed in the late 1970s. He also proposed a separate referendum on whether the [[Shetland Islands]] ought to be part of a devolved [[Scotland]]. Abse was briefly chairman of the Welsh Affairs Select Committee when it was first set up, but resigned in November 1981. One of the reasons he opposed devolution was that he thought some in Wales, whom he called \"fanatics\", wanted to use it to promote the use of the [[Welsh language]].\n\nAbse added to his reputation for taking maverick stances by strongly urging that British forces be withdrawn from [[Northern Ireland]]. He opposed [[nuclear power]] and [[nuclear weapons]], and criticised [[Margaret Thatcher]] for insisting that [[Argentina]] unconditionally surrender over the [[Falkland Islands]]. He supported British membership of the [[European Union|European Communities]]. His support for liberal divorce laws led him to propose a new 'child-centred' divorce reform in the early 1980s; the bill was piloted by [[Martin Stevens]], Conservative MP for [[Fulham (UK Parliament constituency)|Fulham]].\n\nAbse was elected for the renamed seat of [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]] in 1983, but retired from Parliament in 1987. His nomination for a seat in the House of Lords was vetoed by Margaret Thatcher.<ref name=\"Guardian obit\">{{cite web|last1=Goodman|first1=Geoffrey|title=Leo Abse |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/aug/21/labour.houseofcommons |website=The Guardian |accessdate=16 June 2017 |date=20 August 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Retirement and later writings==\nThe first of the books Abse wrote following retirement, ''Margaret, Daughter of Beatrice'' (1989), is a \"psycho-biography\" of Margaret Thatcher, taking its title from the observation that while Mrs Thatcher frequently referred to her father, she claimed not to have had anything to say to her mother from the age of 15.\n\nIn ''Wotan, My Enemy'' (1994) Abse took a psychoanalytic approach to explaining the origin of British hostility to Germany and the idea of the European Union. In ''The Man behind the Smile: Tony Blair and the Politics of Perversion'' (1996), Abse highlighted some of the aspects of [[Tony Blair]] that were later to be cited by Blair's opponents on the left. A revised edition, ''Tony Blair: The Man who Lost His Smile'' (2003), was published in the United States). In this edition Abse took the opportunity to claim that he had paid off a [[blackmail]]er who had been targeting a fellow Welsh MP [[George Thomas, 1st Viscount Tonypandy|George Thomas]] (Speaker of the House of Commons from 1976 to 1983), on the basis of Thomas's (closeted) homosexuality.\n\nFinally, in ''Fellatio, Masochism, Politics and Love'' (1997), Abse drew attention to the fact that fellatio had been unspoken of a generation before but had since come to be seen as an essential part of casual sexual relationships. He analysed the tendency for men to engage in risky behaviour by placing their trust in women whom they barely knew and linked it to political developments.\n\n==Memorial==\nA bust of Abse was unveiled at the [[National Museum of Wales]] in Cardiff on 22 October 2009. The sculpture was funded by the firm of solicitors he founded, Leo Abse and Cohen, and was made by Abse's second cousin, Luke Shepherd.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/8320344.stm |title=Bust of radical MP Abse unveiled |publisher=[[BBC]] |date=22 October 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091025235012/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/wales/8320344.stm |archivedate=25 October 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nAbse was played by actor Anthony O'Donnell in the TV series ''A Very English Scandal''.\n\n==Publications==\n*''Private Member'' (MacDonald, London, 1973)\n*''Margaret, Daughter of Beatrice'' (Jonathan Cape, London, 1989)\n*''Wotan, My Enemy'' (Robson Books, London, 1994)\n*''Tony Blair: The Man behind the Smile'' (Robson Books, London, 1996)\n*''Fellatio, Masochism, Politics and Love'' (Robson Books, London, 1997)\n*''Tony Blair: The Man who Lost his Smile'' (Robson Books, London, 2003)\n*''The Bi-sexuality of Daniel Defoe: a psychoanalytic survey of the man and his works'' (Karnac Books, London, 2006)\n\n==Further reading==\n*\"Leo Abse\" in ''Parliamentary Profiles A\u2013D'' by [[Andrew Roth]] (Parliamentary Profiles Services Ltd, London, 1984)\n*''Peers, Queers and Commons'' by Stephen Jeffery-Poulter (Routledge, London, 1991)\n*''Quest for Justice: Towards Homosexual Emancipation'' by Antony Grey ([[Sinclair-Stevenson]], London, 1992)\n*\"The Troublemakers...\" by Stephen Cretney, in ''The Continuing Evolution of Family Law'', ed. by N. Lowe and G. Douglas (Jordans, Bristol, 2009).\n*''Family Law in the Twentieth Century: A History'' (Oxford, UK: OUP, 2003)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite web|last1=Goodman|first1=Geoffrey|title=Leo Abse|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2008/aug/21/labour.houseofcommons|website=The Guardian|accessdate=16 June 2017|date=20 August 2008}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.parliament.uk/about/living-heritage/transformingsociety/private-lives/relationships/collections1/sexual-offences-act-1967/leo-abse-mp/ Leo Abse- 50th Anniversary of the 1967 Sexual Offences Act - UK Parliament Living Heritage]\n*[https://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/life_and_style/article632537.ece Leo Abse and his brother Dannie] - a joint interview in ''The Times'' November 2006\n*[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/leo-abse-labour-mp-whose-parliamentary-bills-helped-liberalise-british-society-904024.html Obituary in The Independent] by [[Tam Dalyell]]\n*[http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/comment/obituaries/article4573641.ece Times obit, August 2008]\n*[http://paulflynnmp.typepad.com/my_weblog/2008/08/leo-abse---backbenchers-backbencher.html Paul Flynn MP: Leo Abse - backbenchers\u2019 backbencher - Chutzpah and contentment August 2008]\n*[https://www.theguardian.com/gayrights/story/0,,2109785,00.html Coming out of the dark ages] (article from [[The Observer]], 24 June 2007, which includes an interview with Abse)\n*[http://respectance.com/Leo_Abse/memorial Leo Abse Memorial]\n*[http://www.socialistunity.com/?p=2746 Socialist Unity: Remember the good soldier, August 2008]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Granville West, Baron Granville-West|Granville West]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title =[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Pontypool (UK Parliament constituency)|Pontypool]]|years=[[1958 Pontypool by-election|1958]]\u2013[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\n}}\n{{s-non|reason=Constituency abolished }}\n{{s-new|constituency}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Torfaen (UK Parliament constituency)|Torfaen]]|years=[[1983 United Kingdom general election|1983]]\u2013[[1987 United Kingdom general election|1987]]\n}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Paul Murphy (British politician)|Paul Murphy]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Abse, Leo}}\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Councillors in Cardiff]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour Party MPs]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Cardiff]]\n[[Category:People from Cwmbran]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1955\u20131959]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1959\u20131964]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1964\u20131966]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1966\u20131970]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1970\u20131974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974\u20131979]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1974]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1979\u20131983]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 1983\u20131987]]\n[[Category:Welsh Jews]]\n[[Category:Welsh people of Polish descent]]\n[[Category:Welsh writers]]\n[[Category:British people of Polish-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n[[Category:1917 births]]\n[[Category:2008 deaths]]\n[[Category:Abse family|Leo]]\n[[Category:Welsh Labour councillors]]\n", "name_user": "Bmcln1", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leo_Abse"}
{"title_page": "Some Say (Nea song)", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name          = Some Say\n| cover         = Nea - Some Say.png\n| type          = single\n| artist        = Nea\n| album         =\n| released      = {{start date|2019|9|6|df=y}}\n| recorded      =\n| genre         = <!-- Please source genres. -->\n| length        = {{duration|m=2|s=55}} <small>(original version)</small><br>\n{{duration|m=3|s=06}} <small>([[Felix Jaehn]] remix)</small>\n| label         = {{hlist|Kookie Diamond|Linnea S\u00f6dahl|Milkshake|[[Sony Music|Sony Music Entertainment Sweden]]}}\n| writer        = {{hlist|Bryn Christopher|Linn\u00e9a S\u00f6dahl}}\n| producer      = {{hlist|Hitimpulse|Vincent Kottkamp}}\n| chronology    = Nea\n| next_title    = Still Ain't You\n| next_year     = 2019\n| misc          = {{External music video|{{YouTube|fAiSwh_wSuY|\"Some Say\"}}}}\n}}\n\"'''Some Say'''\" is a song by Swedish singer Nea and was released as her debut single on 6 September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.broadwayworld.com/bwwmusic/article/Swedish-Artist-Nea-Debuts-With-Single-Some-Say-20190906|title=Swedish Artist Nea Debuts With Single 'Some Say'|website=[[BroadwayWorld]]|date=6 September 2019|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> Following the song's success in Europe in late 2019 and early 2020, the song was remixed by German DJ [[Felix Jaehn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.scandipop.co.uk/song-nea-some-say/|title=Song: Nea - 'Some Say' (Felix Jaehn remix)|website=Scandipop|date=14 January 2020|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref> The remix was released on 10 January 2020. The song has since reached the top ten in Belgium (Wallonia), Switzerland and Norway, as well as the top 20 in Belgium (Flanders), Denmark, France, Germany and Sweden. The song interpolates [[Eiffel 65]]'s \"[[Blue (Da Ba Dee)]]\" (1998).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://substreammagazine.com/2019/09/nea-some-say/|title=Swedish pop songwriter Nea shares debut single \"Some Say\"|last=Berard|first=Oleva|website=[[Substream Magazine]]|date=6 September 2019|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Credits and personnel==\nCredits adapted from [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://listen.tidal.com/album/115010463/credits|title=Some Say / Nea|via=[[Tidal (service)|Tidal]]|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Div col}}\n* Linn\u00e9a S\u00f6dahl \u2013 vocals, songwriting, composer\n* Bryn Christopher \u2013 songwriting, composer\n* Vincent Kottkamp \u2013 production, composer, guitar, mixing engineering\n* Hitimpulse \u2013 production, mixing engineering\n* Alexsej Vlasenko \u2013 composer, synthesizer\n* Jonas Kalisch \u2013 composer, bass\n* Henrik Meinke \u2013 composer, drums\n* Jeremy Chacon \u2013 composer, keyboards\n* Lex Barkey \u2013 master engineering\n{{Div col end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (2019\u20132020)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{single chart|Austria|33|artist=Nea|song=Some Say|rowheader=true|accessdate=2 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Flanders|12|artist=Nea|song=Some Say|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Wallonia|3|artist=Nea|song=Some Say|rowheader=true|accessdate=4 April 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Denmark|17|artist=Nea|song=Some Say|rowheader=true|accessdate=26 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|France|14|artist=Nea|song=Some Say|rowheader=true|accessdate=26 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Germany2|17|songid=1903571|artist=Nea|song=Some Say|rowheader=true|accessdate=27 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Norway|6|artist=Nea|song=Some Say|rowheader=true|accessdate=26 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Sweden|12|artist=Nea|song=Some Say|rowheader=true|accessdate=26 March 2020}}\n|-\n{{single chart|Switzerland|5|artist=Nea|song=Some Say|rowheader=true|accessdate=26 March 2020}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=France|artist=Nea|title=Some Say|award=Gold|type=si