creen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role|Outstanding Performance by a Male Actor in a Leading Role]]\n|Jamie Bell\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1154689.stm|title=Jamie's dance to fame|date=2001-02-06|access-date=2020-01-03|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103103030/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1154689.stm|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role|Outstanding Performance by a Female Actor in a Supporting Role]]\n|Julie Walters\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/7th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|title=The 7th Annual Screen Actors Guild Awards {{!}} Screen Actors Guild Awards|website=www.sagawards.org|language=en|access-date=2020-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190706041918/https://www.sagawards.org/awards/nominees-and-recipients/7th-annual-screen-actors-guild-awards|archive-date=6 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|[[Screen Actors Guild Award for Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture|Outstanding Performance by a Cast in a Motion Picture]]\n|\n|{{nom}}\n|<ref name=\":5\" />\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |[[London Film Critics' Circle]]\n|British Newcomer of the Year\n|Julie Walters|Jamie Bell\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1172629.stm|title=Awards flow for Billy Elliot|date=2001-02-15|access-date=2020-01-03|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103103036/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/entertainment/1172629.stm|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|-\n|British Producer of the Year\n|Greg Brenman\nJon Finn\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|British Director of the Year\n|Jamie Bell|Stephen Daldry\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|British Film of the Year\n|''Billy Elliot''|\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|British Actress of the Year \n|Stephen Daldry|Julie Walters\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref name=\":6\" />\n|-\n|[[Motovun Film Festival]]\n|Propeller Award\n|''Billy Elliot''|\n|{{Won}}\n|<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://motovunfilmfestival.com/en/motovun-film-festival-has-a-new-cinema-cinema-billy/|title=Motovun Film Festival has a new cinema - Cinema Billy!|date=2019-02-21|website=Motovun Film Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200103111053/https://motovunfilmfestival.com/en/motovun-film-festival-has-a-new-cinema-cinema-billy/|archive-date=3 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Stage musical==\n{{main|Billy Elliot the Musical}}\nAfter the film's release, English singer-songwriter [[Elton John]] collaborated with the film's screenwriter [[Lee Hall (playwright)|Lee Hall]] to produce a musical adaptation of the film, which premiered 31 March 2005 at the [[Victoria Palace Theatre]] on the [[West End theatre|West End]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/musicals/a-bluecollar-tale-mines-rich-musical-seam-20100404-rlig.html|title=A blue-collar tale mines rich musical seam|last=Jones|first=Chris|date=2010-04-04|website=The Sydney Morning Herald|language=en|access-date=2020-01-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200102205048/https://www.smh.com.au/entertainment/musicals/a-bluecollar-tale-mines-rich-musical-seam-20100404-rlig.html|archive-date=2 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Many of the film's crew took part in the stage production, including director [[Stephen Daldry]] and choreographer [[Peter Darling]]. The musical received positive reviews and ran for over 4,000 performances before closing in April 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.londontheatre.co.uk/reviews/billy-elliot-victoria-palace-theatre-2005|title=Billy Elliot - Victoria Palace Theatre 2005|newspaper=London Theatre Guide|access-date=18 December 2016|date=11 May 2005|last=Brown|first=Peter|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200101130136/https://www.londontheatre.co.uk/reviews/billy-elliot-victoria-palace-theatre-2005|archive-date=1 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/35069692?client=safari|title=Billy Elliot musical dances out of West End|website=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=11 December 2015|accessdate=9 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* ''[[Brassed Off]]''\n* ''[[The Stars Look Down]]''\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n* [http://cinema.com/articles/160/billy-elliot-production-notes.phtml Production notes]\n\n==Further reading==\n* Jacqueline Jones, \"Small Towns and Big Dreams: Meditations on Two Mining-Town Movies\" ''Perspectives on History'' (Feb 2011) 49#2 pp 30\u201331, compares film with \"[[How Green Was My Valley]]\".\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0249462}}\n* {{mojo title|billyelliot}}\n* {{rotten-tomatoes|billy_elliot}}\n* {{metacritic film|billy-elliot}}\n\n{{The Stars Look Down}}\n{{Lee Hall}}\n{{Stephen Daldry}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title= Awards for ''Billy Elliot''\n|list=\n{{BAFTA Best British Film}}\n{{BIFA BestBritishFilm}}\n{{GLAAD Media Award for Outstanding Film \u2013 Wide Release}}\n{{London Film Critics Circle Award for British Film of the Year}}\n{{Empire Award for Best British Film}}\n}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Billy Elliot}}\n[[Category:2000 films]]\n[[Category:2000s dance films]]\n[[Category:2000s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:British films]]\n[[Category:British comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:British coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:British dance films]]\n[[Category:2000s coming-of-age comedy films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Stephen Daldry]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Stephen Warbeck]]\n[[Category:Best British Film Empire Award winners]]\n[[Category:Films about ballet]]\n[[Category:Films about the labor movement]]\n[[Category:Films set in County Durham]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1984]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1985]]\n[[Category:Films set in 1999]]\n[[Category:Films shot in England]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Northumberland]]\n[[Category:UK miners' strike (1984\u201385)]]\n[[Category:BAFTA winners (films)]]\n[[Category:BBC Films films]]\n[[Category:StudioCanal films]]\n[[Category:Working Title Films films]]\n[[Category:Films adapted into plays]]\n[[Category:Mining in film]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Lee Hall]]\n[[Category:2000s coming-of-age drama films]]\n[[Category:2000 directorial debut films]]\n", "name_user": "Lizzy150", "label": "safe", "comment": "prose changes as per GA review", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Elliot"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Barbados", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Barbados}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Barbados\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Barbados]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 17 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=17|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 46<ref name=\"gis-2april\">{{Cite web|url=https://gisbarbados.gov.bb/blog/24-hour-curfew-for-barbados-from-friday/ |title=24-Hour Curfew For Barbados From 6:00 p.m. Friday |date=2 April 2020 |accessdate=3 April 2020 | work=GIS Barbados}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Barbados]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 17 March 2020, the Minister of Health and Wellness, Lt Col [[Jeffrey Bostic]] confirmed the first two cases in [[Barbados]]. They will remain in isolation until they recover.<ref name=\"Case_1_2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationnews.com/nationnews/news/244434/barbados-records-covid-19 |title=Barbados records two cases of COVID-19 |date=17 March 2020 |work=nationnews}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March 2020, three more cases were confirmed,<ref name=loop1>{{cite web |url=https://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/covid-19-three-more-tests-come-back-positive-barbados |title=COVID-19: Three more tests come back positive in Barbados |last=Gooding |first=Kerri |work=Loop News Barbados |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> bringing the total number of cases to five, including the husband of the first case, as well as a cruise ship passenger and a person from New York.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nBy 24 March 2020, there had been 18 confirmed cases in total.<ref name=\"barbadostoday1\">{{Cite web|url=https://barbadostoday.bb/2020/03/24/covid-19-update-only-one-new-case-today/ |title=COVID- 19 Update: Only one new case today |date=24 March 2020 |work=Barbados Today}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March 2020, the Minister of Health announced that the total number of cases reached 26. By that date, Barbados had conducted 234 tests overall.<ref name=\"loop-27march\">{{cite news |title=Barbados COVID-19 cases stand at 26 as of March 27, 1 pm |url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/barbados-covid-19-cases-jump-26-march-27-1-pm |access-date=28 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020 |work=Loop News}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2020, Acting Chief Medical Officer, Dr Anton Best, announced seven new cases taking the total number of cases up to 33. Of those cases 19 were imported, 11 were identified through contact tracing, and 2 were still being investigated. 16 of the cases were males and 17 were females. By that date, Barbados had conducted 287 tests overall and there was no evidence of [[community transmission|community spread]].<ref name=\"gisbarbados-29march\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19 Update: National Count At 33 |url=https://gisbarbados.gov.bb/blog/covid-19-update-national-count-at-33/ |date=29 March 2020 |work=GIS Barbados}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2020, Minister of Health and Wellness Jeffrey Bostic announced one new case, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 34.<ref name=\"Nationnews-30march\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationnews.com/nationnews/news/244713/34-confirmed-covid-19-barbados|title=34 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Barbados |date= 30 March 2020 | work= nationnews}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April 2020, acting Prime Minister Santia Bradshaw announced that 11 tests were positive the day before, 31 March 2020, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 45 and the total number of tests performed to 382.<ref name=\"youtube-31march\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AEgVlrCjCqA |title=COVID-19 Update (1st April, 2020) feat. Acting PM Hon. Santia Bradshaw, M.P |date=1 April 2020 | work=PMOBarbados YouTube Channel}}</ref>\n\n==Prevention efforts==\nAs a result of the outbreak, the government closed all schools and limited gatherings to 25. On 19 March, the Government announced that all arrivals from the UK, Europe and the US would be quarantined for 14 days.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Public health emergency===\n\nOn 26 March 2020, [[Prime Minister of Barbados|Prime Minister]] [[Mia Mottley]] announced that the country reached 24 cases and would be entering stage three of the COVID-19 National Preparedness Plan:<ref name=\"loop2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/barbadians-enters-stage-3-curfew-march-28 |title=COVID-19: Barbados enters Stage 3, curfew from March 28 |date=26 March 2020 |work=Loop Barbados}}</ref><ref name=\"gisbarbados1\">{{Cite web|url=https://gisbarbados.gov.bb/blog/extracts-emergency-management-covid-19-order-2020-fbclidiwar32cxrvq5zqfy0msm6nybss1_90a-nygoo3isvesndcghk-wagaik1dz48/ |title=Extracts - Emergency Management (COVID-19) Order, 2020 |date=27 March 2020 |work=GIS Barbados}}</ref>\n\n* A public health emergency has been declared\n* A curfew from Saturday, March 28, to Tuesday, April 14, 8:00&nbsp;p.m. to 6:00&nbsp;a.m.\n* Persons are confined to their places of residence during curfew hours\n* Limited movement during the day\n* Continue to practise physical distancing of six feet between persons\n* The plan is being implemented in a phased manner based on the intensity of spread\n\nBusinesses in the private sector will be closed from 28 March 2020 by 8:00 pm until 15 April 2020, except for those excluded by the government such as groceries, pharmacies, gas stations and farms, with specific allowed operating hours for each type of business. Restaurants can open but only for drive-through and take away services.\n\nPeople contravening the order without a reasonable explanation will be liable to a fine of BBD $50,000, one year in prison, or both.\n\n== See also==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Barbados|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Barbados]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Caribbean|Barbados]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Barbados}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Barbados\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Barbados]]\n| first_case = \n| arrival_date = 17 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=17|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[China]]\n| recovery_cases = 0\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 46<ref name=\"youtube-31march\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=AEgVlrCjCqA |title=COVID-19 Update (1st April, 2020) feat. Acting PM Hon. Santia Bradshaw, M.P |date=1 April 2020 | work=PMOBarbados YouTube Channel}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached [[Barbados]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 17 March 2020, the Minister of Health and Wellness, Lt Col [[Jeffrey Bostic]] confirmed the first two cases in [[Barbados]]. They will remain in isolation until they recover.<ref name=\"Case_1_2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationnews.com/nationnews/news/244434/barbados-records-covid-19 |title=Barbados records two cases of COVID-19 |date=17 March 2020 |work=nationnews}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March 2020, three more cases were confirmed,<ref name=loop1>{{cite web |url=https://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/covid-19-three-more-tests-come-back-positive-barbados |title=COVID-19: Three more tests come back positive in Barbados |last=Gooding |first=Kerri |work=Loop News Barbados |date=19 March 2020 |access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref> bringing the total number of cases to five, including the husband of the first case, as well as a cruise ship passenger and a person from New York.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\nBy 24 March 2020, there had been 18 confirmed cases in total.<ref name=\"barbadostoday1\">{{Cite web|url=https://barbadostoday.bb/2020/03/24/covid-19-update-only-one-new-case-today/ |title=COVID- 19 Update: Only one new case today |date=24 March 2020 |work=Barbados Today}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 March 2020, the Minister of Health announced that the total number of cases reached 26. By that date, Barbados had conducted 234 tests overall.<ref name=\"loop-27march\">{{cite news |title=Barbados COVID-19 cases stand at 26 as of March 27, 1 pm |url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/barbados-covid-19-cases-jump-26-march-27-1-pm |access-date=28 March 2020 |date=27 March 2020 |work=Loop News}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 March 2020, Acting Chief Medical Officer, Dr Anton Best, announced seven new cases taking the total number of cases up to 33. Of those cases 19 were imported, 11 were identified through contact tracing, and 2 were still being investigated. 16 of the cases were males and 17 were females. By that date, Barbados had conducted 287 tests overall and there was no evidence of [[community transmission|community spread]].<ref name=\"gisbarbados-29march\">{{cite news |title=COVID-19 Update: National Count At 33 |url=https://gisbarbados.gov.bb/blog/covid-19-update-national-count-at-33/ |date=29 March 2020 |work=GIS Barbados}}</ref>\n\nOn 30 March 2020, Minister of Health and Wellness Jeffrey Bostic announced one new case, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 34.<ref name=\"Nationnews-30march\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationnews.com/nationnews/news/244713/34-confirmed-covid-19-barbados|title=34 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Barbados |date= 30 March 2020 | work= nationnews}}</ref>\n\nOn 1 April 2020, acting Prime Minister Santia Bradshaw announced that 11 tests were positive the day before, 31 March 2020, bringing the total number of confirmed cases to 45 and the total number of tests performed to 382.<ref name=\"youtube-31march\" />\n\n==Prevention efforts==\nAs a result of the outbreak, the government closed all schools and limited gatherings to 25. On 19 March, the Government announced that all arrivals from the UK, Europe and the US would be quarantined for 14 days.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}}\n\n===Public health emergency===\n\nOn 26 March 2020, [[Prime Minister of Barbados|Prime Minister]] [[Mia Mottley]] announced that the country reached 24 cases and would be entering stage three of the COVID-19 National Preparedness Plan:<ref name=\"loop2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.loopnewsbarbados.com/content/barbadians-enters-stage-3-curfew-march-28 |title=COVID-19: Barbados enters Stage 3, curfew from March 28 |date=26 March 2020 |work=Loop Barbados}}</ref><ref name=\"gisbarbados1\">{{Cite web|url=https://gisbarbados.gov.bb/blog/extracts-emergency-management-covid-19-order-2020-fbclidiwar32cxrvq5zqfy0msm6nybss1_90a-nygoo3isvesndcghk-wagaik1dz48/ |title=Extracts - Emergency Management (COVID-19) Order, 2020 |date=27 March 2020 |work=GIS Barbados}}</ref>\n\n* A public health emergency has been declared\n* A curfew from Saturday, March 28, to Tuesday, April 14, 8:00&nbsp;p.m. to 6:00&nbsp;a.m.\n* Persons are confined to their places of residence during curfew hours\n* Limited movement during the day\n* Continue to practise physical distancing of six feet between persons\n* The plan is being implemented in a phased manner based on the intensity of spread\n\nBusinesses in the private sector will be closed from 28 March 2020 by 8:00 pm until 15 April 2020, except for those excluded by the government such as groceries, pharmacies, gas stations and farms, with specific allowed operating hours for each type of business. Restaurants can open but only for drive-through and take away services.\n\nPeople contravening the order without a reasonable explanation will be liable to a fine of BBD $50,000, one year in prison, or both.\n\n== See also==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Barbados|coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory|Barbados]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Caribbean|Barbados]]\n", "name_user": "Fireman biff", "label": "safe", "comment": "+source for case count", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Barbados"}
